## Source And Evidence Weighting

When evidence conflicts, use this order: target files/commands/tests and
maintainer decisions; reviewed repo harness docs; approved harness-learning
patterns; sibling examples, external ideas, and generated reports. Examples and
reports are not contracts until promoted into repo-owned docs, tests, schemas,
templates, or code.

Planning rules: one bounded item at a time; baseline verification when
practical; smallest-correct gate before new surface area; repeated feedback
becomes a rule, sensor, test, or durable doc. Behavior, verification, status,
and evidence must agree before passing or shipped. Make failures
agent-oriented: what failed, why it matters, where to repair.

## Smallest Correct Work Gate

Before implementation, prefer: no change, deletion, documentation,
configuration, existing behavior, standard library, native platform feature,
existing dependency, one local change, then minimum new code or harness surface.
Do not add speculative features, configurability, abstractions, workflows, or
dependencies unless named. Do not cut trust boundaries, data-loss prevention,
security, accessibility, platform parity, or explicit requirements. Record the
ceiling and upgrade path for intentional simplification.

## Task Buckets

Use small buckets: `active`, `accepted`, `candidate`, `debt`, `completed`,
`archived`.

## Status Lifecycle

Use explicit statuses: `candidate`, `accepted`, `planned`, `in_progress`,
`blocked`, `validated`, `shipped`, `superseded`, or `abandoned`.

## Surface Impact Checklist

For every accepted item, classify surfaces before implementation starts.

| Surface | Scope Prompt |
| --- | --- |
| Local repo harness | Instructions, state, harness docs, sensors, release controls |
| Generated or owned harness files | Harness file, section, manifest rule, review-required placeholder |
| CLI or tool runtime | Command, flag, JSON, exit code, report, default |
| Existing project files | Project instructions, specs, workflows, scripts, docs |
| CI or hosted automation | Workflows, Action usage, summaries, reports, permissions, artifacts |
| Optional workflow scaffolds | Setup, teardown, push, or PR automation remains opt-in |
| Tests and fixtures | Local checks, generated snapshots, fixtures, representative task runs |
| Release surface | Packaging, tag, SBOM, provenance, release notes, rollback |
| Research and source records | Primary-source evidence, project-owned source records |
| Security and privacy | Secrets, local paths, private code, permissions, network, cost |
| Platform contracts | macOS, Windows, Linux, runtimes, runner labels, adapters |
| Docs and UX | User docs, help output, startup instructions, first-run guidance |

If a surface is out of scope, say so. Keep target-local preferences, generated
defaults, and CI automation separate.

